import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter a positive integer: ");
        int n = scanner.nextInt();

        boolean isPowerOfThree = isPowerOfThree(n);

        System.out.println("Is " + n + " a power of three? " + isPowerOfThree);
    }

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 0) {
            return false;
        }

        if (n == 0) {
            return false;
        }

        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }

        return n == 1;
    }
}

Explanation:
This code uses the while loop to repeatedly divide n by 3 until the remainder is no longer equal to 0. If the final value of n is equal to 1, then it means that n is a power of three. Otherwise, it is not a power of three.
The code handles negative and zero inputs by returning false in these cases.

